remely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Gospatric was born in 1135, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Gospatric III of Dunbar, was 45 and her mother, Heiress of Hirsel and Greenlaw Deirdre Hirsel,, was 41. She had at least 2 sons with Gille Brigte Mac Dufugan 2nd Earl Of Angus. She died in 1154, in Forfar, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1135–1154":"1135–1154","1122–1182":"1122–1182","1124–1201":"1124–1201","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1118–1187":"1118–1187","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1154–1207":"1154–1207","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1094–1131":"1094–1131","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1094":"1094","1182":"1182","1118":"1118","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1124":"1124","1166":"1166","1122":"1122","about 1152":"umbes 1152","about 1120":"umbes 1120","1207":"1207","Dunottar Castle- Stonehaven- Aberdeenshire- Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Forfar- Angus- Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1135–1154":"1135–1154","1122–1182":"1122–1182","1124–1201":"1124–1201","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1118–1187":"1118–1187","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","1154–1207":"1154–1207","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1094–1131":"1094–1131","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1094":"1094","1182":"1182","1118":"1118","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1124":"1124","1166":"1166","1122":"1122","about 1152":"noin 1152","about 1120":"noin 1120","1207":"1207","Dunottar Castle- Stonehaven- Aberdeenshire- Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Forfar- Angus- Scotland":"Fo